Chapter 1 - A beginning

This is the first exercise for the Introduction to Open Data Science course. It includes a link to my github repository.

https://github.com/robertscottleigh/IODS-project.git

This week’s work was focused on setting up tools necessary for completing the rest of the course, including the use of Github and Rstudio. Github includes a website and accompanying software and is used for version control. This may be done using a desktop or command-line version. As I will be completing this course on university computers on which I do not have administrator rights, I have opted to simply upload my files directly to Github. A project template was available for use in the course, including three R markdown files for modification. These were modified to include necessary info (name, links to github pages) and knitted to an html document for publication. As this is now my third course in which Rstudio was used, this went very smoothly. I look forward to getting into the data!

Structure and dimensions of data. The dataset consists of results from a questionairre of students. It consists of 7 variables: gender, age, attitude, deep learning, strategic learning, surface learning, and points awwarded on an exam. Individuals (166 total) are in rows and variables measured are in columns. Note that for this report, descriptions of the data are just above the code/plots.

Graphical overview of the data. The ‘ggpairs’ function, which relies on the ‘GGally’ and ‘ggplot2’ packages, plots all variables against one another. This is a quick and easy way to see potential relationships between variables in order to plan further analysis. In this case, gender was plotted as different colors. Graphical representation of the data suggests linear relationships between some of the variables, such as “attitude” vs “stra” and “deep” vs “surf”.

Summary of the variables in the data. The ‘summary’ function allows a text-based overview of a datset, presenting interquartile range, min/max, median, and mean of all numeric variables in a dataset, and numerical representations of categorical variables. This is a very good first step, especially if you are not very familiar with a dataset. In the learning 2014 dataset, the course participants were mostly female (110/166) and their age ranges were from 17-55. The median student age was 22 years old. Performance on the exam ranged from a low of 7 points to a high of 33 points, with an average score of 22.72. The results of survey questions, including the variables attitude, deep, stra, and surf were 1:5 scale.

Based on the graphical representations, attitude, stra, and surf were chosen as explanatory variables for points. The lm() function is used for generating a linear model, and summary() used to display results. This model shows only “attitude” is a statistically significant explanatory variable (p=1.93e-08). The variable “stra” is close to significance (p=0.11716), and the variable “surf” is not significant (0.46563). Only “attitude”" is included in further analysis.

model_1 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
summary(model_1)

The model was refitted with only attitude as an explanatory variable, as that was the only variable which was statistically significant in the initial analysis. The median residual of the model, or difference between the values predicted by the linear model and real experimental values, is 0.43. The y-intercept of the line is 11.6372 (alpha parameter), and the slope of the line is 3.5255 (beta parameter). “Points”" thus increase by a factor of 3.5255 with every increasing point of “attitude”. If the null hypothesis is that the beta parameter of “attitude”" is 0, the p value is 4.12e-09. The R-squared value is 0.1906, suggesting that the variable “attitude” explains 19% of the variation of exam points around the mean. This is not surprising as other factors surely affect exam performance, such as study time, general intelligence, test anxiety, etc.

As linear models rely on basic assumptions about the data, in terms of spread, normality, and lack of outliers, it is necessary to include further analysis of the suitability of the linear model to a particular dataset. This is possible using the plot() function and the ‘which’ = option. This includes pre-defined plots. In whis case, residuals vs fitted, normal Q-Q, and residuals vs leverage were chosen. The residuals vs Fitted plot suggests that there is a decrease in the spread of values as the fitted values increase. This indicates the predictiveness of the model varies with the score. In the Q-Q plot, here is a resonably good fit to the line, suggesting that the errors are normally distributed. Analysis of the Residuals vs Leverage plot suggests that there are no clear outliers.

plot(model_2, which = c(1:2, 5))

Hypotheses:

Based on my distant memories of life as a high school student, I predict the following relationships between the variables. Positive relationships: high alcohol use (high_use) and going out (goout) high alcohol use and absences (absences) Negative relationships: high alcohol use and final grade (G3) high alcohol use and weekly study time (studytime)

Graphical exploration of variables.

high_use vs goout: Students who drink more alcohol appear to go out more. absences: Students who drink more alcohol appear to miss more school.
Final grade: Students who drink more alcohol appear to have a slightly lower grade. Study time: Students who drink more alcohol appear to study less.

library(ggplot2)
g1 <- ggplot(data = alc, aes(x = high_use, y=goout))
g1 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Going out")

g2 <- ggplot(data = alc, aes(x = high_use, y=absences))
g2 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("# of absences")

g3 <- ggplot(data = alc, aes(x = high_use, y=G3))
g3 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Final grade")

g4 <- ggplot(data = alc, aes(x = high_use, y=studytime))
g4 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Weekly study time")

Logistic regression model with high/low alcohol use and goout, absences, G3, and studytime. Summary of model. Statistically significant positive relationships appear between high_use and goout, high_use and absences. Thus students abusing alcohol are more likely to go out and then miss class Statistically significant negative relationships appear between high_use and studytime. Thus, students abusing alcohol unsurprisingly study less.

Odds ratio and confidence intervals. As the odds ratio is greater than 1, there are positive associations of high alcohol use and going out(OR = 2.1), absences (OR = 1.05), and grade (OR =1.01). The confidence interval of final grade (G3) is 0.95-1.07. AS this includes 1, the positive association should not be considered as significant. Going out and absences have 95% confidence intervals in which both lower limits and high limits are above 1, suggesting their significance. As the odds ratio is less than 1, there are negative associations of high alcohol use and study time (OR = 0.54). The 95% confidence interval is well below 1 (0.38-0.75). These findings are in line with my hypotheses, with the exception of final grade, which seems not to be related to abuse of alcohol.

library(dplyr)
high_low.logreg <- glm(high_use ~ goout + absences + G3 + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Explore predictive power of the model.2x2 cross tabulation of predictions vs values and graphic representation. Training error. Comments.

The model was modified in order to use the variables “goout”, “absences”, and “studytime” to predict the abuse of alcohol (high_use). The model was able to correctly predict 246 students not abusing alcohol, while the model predicted that 24 additional students would abuse alcohol, but in fact did not. The model correctly predicted 46 students who would abuse alcohol, but incorrectly predicted 66 students as being alcohol abusers, when in fact they were not. Overall, the number of wrong predictions using the model was 23.56%. If the probability were assigned as 0 or 1 via guessing the percentage of wrong predictions would be 29.31% or 70.68%, respectively. These results suggest the model does indeed perform better than random guessing, but that there are still more variables needed to accurately predict the students that would abuse alcohol. I actually find the graphical representation more difficult to interpret than the tabular forms.

high_low.logreg <- glm(high_use ~ goout + absences + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")
probabilities <- predict(high_low.logreg, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = ifelse(probability > 0.5, TRUE, FALSE))

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
print("Average number of wrong predictions using model")
## [1] "Average number of wrong predictions using model"
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2356021
print("Guess of 0")
## [1] "Guess of 0"
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 0)
## [1] 0.2931937
print("Guess of 1")
## [1] "Guess of 1"
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 1)
## [1] 0.7068063

10-fold cross validation on the model is performed by setting k=10. The model prediction error is 24.08%, which is better than 26% from the Datacamp exercises.

library(boot)
high_low.cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = high_low.logreg, K = 10)
print("Model prediction error with 10-fold cross validation")
## [1] "Model prediction error with 10-fold cross validation"
high_low.cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2434555

Using the scale() function, the “Boston” dataset is scaled so that the mean for each variable is 0. The scaled dataset was converted to a data frame for further manipulation. The “quantile()” function is used to generate cutoffs/break points at 25% intervals for the crim variable within the Boston dataset. This will be used for generation of catergorical variables. The cut() function is used to generate a new categorical variable called “crime”, which is based on the 25% intervals given the names “low”, “med_low”, “med_high”, and “high”. The original “crim” variable is removed and the new “crime” categorical variable is added. The number of rows of the dataset are applied to a variable n, in order to sample 80% of those rows to a training dataset called “train”, and the remaining rows to a test dataset called “test”. This divides the observations for the purpose of developing computational models.

ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) was fit onto the training dataset using the lda() function, based on the categorical crime variable versus all other variables (indicated by the ~). The lda analysis was plotted including a function for arrows. LDA is used for dimension reduction and classification. It basically seeks to separate the variables as compared to the target variable “crime”.

lda.fit <- lda(crime~., data = train)
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch= classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

The original “crime” values from the test dataset were saved to a new variable called test_classes, and the variable deleted from the dataset. The LDA model from the previous step was used in conjunction with the predict() function to generate predicted values, and these were shown in a table versus the real values. The model was reasonably good at predicting the correct crime category.

test_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(correct = test_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)

The Boston dataset variables were scaled, and both the Euclidean and Manhattan distances were calculated. These show how far the variables are from one another, using two different measurements, and are one component of the k-means clustering algorithm. Based on the plot of the twcss function, it is apparent that the optimal number of clusters is around 2, as this is the point at which the data starts to vary. These clusters were plotted using the pairs function for all variables, which is slightly hard to interpret.
